    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay thanks. i'm kinda nervous about the electrical part. you mentioned the capacitor—what does that actually do in the unit? is it a common thing for them to just die out of nowhere like that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The capacitor acts like an electrical \"kick-start\" that gives the motor a burst of energy to overcome inertia and begin spinning, so without it, the motor just hums while trying to turn. Yes, capacitors are very common to fail unexpectedly because they degrade over time due to heat, vibration, and age, often leaving the rest of the system intact but the fan frozen. Since you just turned off the breaker, you can safely inspect the unit visually for obvious damage, but do not attempt to touch any internal components until a professional confirms it is fully safe.",
